<!doctype html>
<!--
  facilitator-approved.step-2.mjml — Week 3 after approval: keep praying for your FPG.
  Source: Drip Emails for facilitators Sign-up - Copy.docx (Email 4 — "Keep Praying" variant).
  Note: the doc had a duplicate "Email 4" titled "Keeping current" with no week
  label; it was omitted pending clarification.
-->
<html><body style="font-family: sans-serif; max-width: 640px; margin: 0 auto; color: #1f2937;">
  <h2 style="color: #1f2937;">Keep Praying for your FPG</h2>
  <p>Hi {{ contact_display_name }},</p>

  <p>
    God wants all people to be saved and to come to a knowledge of the truth
    (1 Timothy 2:4). From the beginning of time, His plan wasn't just for
    one country or one type of person, but for the whole world. Frontier
    People Groups make up the 1.9 billion people who have the least access
    to the gospel out of anyone on the planet. In prayer we align our hearts
    with the very heartbeat of God and stand in agreement with Jesus' Great
    Commission. Lord, we believe Your promise from Revelation 7:9: that
    every nation, tribe, people, and language will be standing before the
    throne and the Lamb.
  </p>

  <h3 style="color: #374151;">The Mission: What to Pray</h3>
  <p>
    Since adopters will come from a variety of experiences, your organization
    may want to guide them in ways to pray for the "open door." Even the
    Apostle Paul asked for prayer that "God may open a door for our message,
    so that we may proclaim the mystery of Christ" (Colossians 4:3). Your
    organization may already have developed prayer guides to pass along.
    Here are just a few ways to consider asking adopters to pray:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>For Access:</strong> Pray that governments and leaders in closed countries will allow believers to enter, and to live peaceful lives (1 Timothy 2:1-4).</li>
    <li><strong>For Translation:</strong> Pray that the Bible will be translated into every mother tongue so people can hear God speaking their own language.</li>
    <li><strong>For Power:</strong> Pray that the Gospel would come to them not just with words, but with the power of the Holy Spirit (1 Thessalonians 1:5).</li>
    <li><strong>For Boldness:</strong> Pray that God would enable His servants to speak His word with clear, powerful, effective witness in Jesus' name (Acts 4:29-30).</li>
    <li><strong>For Local Leaders:</strong> Pray that God would raise up a "Paul" within these groups — someone from within the culture who will meet Jesus and lead their own people to Him.</li>
    <li><strong>For Light:</strong> Ask God to shine His light into hearts that have been in spiritual darkness for generations, as promised in 2 Corinthians 4:6.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    In 1727, a small community of believers in Herrnhut, Germany, began
    praying wholeheartedly that the darkest places in the world could hear
    the gospel. It launched a 100-year prayer movement that coincided with
    the launching of world-changing missionary activity. Spiritual work in
    missions is supported by faithful prayer warriors. Will you be one?
  </p>

  <h3 style="color: #374151;">Sample Weekly Prayer Rhythm</h3>
  <p>Pray daily or weekly for the Frontier People Group(s) in various ways. Here is one example:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Holy Spirit's work to be known; hearts being drawn to Christ; dreams and visions of Jesus; spiritual hunger; God's mercy poured out among this group.</li>
    <li>Barriers and spiritual strongholds to be removed; God's favor in overcoming obstacles related to politics, religion, culture, language, and location.</li>
    <li>Workers to be empowered, protected, and strengthened.</li>
    <li>Access to the gospel through digital means, marketplace ministry, Bible translation, creative access, and other means.</li>
    <li>Networks and organizations to collaborate to multiply the ministry engagement among the FPG(s).</li>
    <li>The few global Christians in this people group, once they exist, to share Christ lovingly, boldly, and strategically. Pray for their encouragement.</li>
    <li>For more people and ministries to pray for, advocate for, and adopt the FPG(s).</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    We don't pray perfectly, we just start. May you be greatly blessed as
    you lift up this FPG to the Lord of the Harvest.
  </p>

  <p>With you in the work,<br/>The Joshua Project Team</p>

  <p style="color: #9ca3af; font-size: 12px; margin-top: 32px;">
    Reply "unsubscribe" to stop receiving this series.
  </p>
</body></html>
